	   <tr><td colspan=2>I've looked back over the past few pages on this board and haven't seen this issue addressed, so I wanted to bring it up and get some enlightenment. <br><br>In some of the groups that I have been in over the past week there has been a problem with the casters drawing too much attention during the fight. With an enchanter in the group it's not that big of an issue, but when you don't have one available it falls to the melees to pull the mob off the caster. Since I have another character that's a ranger, I'm used to being the one who does this. Flame lick or snare followed by a couple of taunts while beating on the offending mob has always done the trick. Well, last night we had the following mix:<br><br>2 shamans<br>2 monks<br>1 wiz<br>1 cleric<br><br>The monks were tanking/pulling, shamans were buffing and backup healing with a little damage dealing when buffs were good and cleric had full mana, wiz was nuking, and cleric was healing. The wizard was doing a good job of letting us build a lot of agro before he nuked, but every now and then a mob would jump him. Since we only had monks in the group and we don't get taunt, the only way we could get the mob off was to beat on it until it came after one of us. Sometimes this would take a while, especially with multiple mobs because the others would stay on the first one and I would switch targets and try to pull off the caster. I'm dual wielding a goranga spiked club (YES!!! Finally got one, I'll post how I did this at level 20 in a bit) and a polished steel ulak in my offhand. For those of you not aware of the goranga's stats they are as follows:<br><br>12 damage<br>23 delay<br>+5 ac<br>+2 str<br><br>Here's my question - Is there anything that we as monks can do to pull additional agro in a situation like this? Feign death is the end all and be all of dropping agro, but without taunt or spells we pretty much have to rely on straight weapon damage to pull agro when necessary. I know that we shouldn't be trying to pull agro on a regular basis, but there are times when it is necessary.<br><br>In talking to some other characters, I've had a rogue tell me that if they pickpocket during a fight it will pull the mob almost every time if they get caught doing it, and I had someone else tell me that they will beg during a fight to pull/hold agro. Does anyone know if begging from the mob you are fighting will help pull agro? Or is this wishful thinking on the part of people who are doing this? If it helps, then this might be an alternative for us monks in that situation. A drawback would be that as you raise your beg skill it might become less effective. <br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Mon Apr&nbsp;&nbsp;8 12:48:40 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Jheran 54 Human Monk<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=310212" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=310212</a><br>Victorex 33 Wood Elf Ranger<br><br></td></tr>
