	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.45]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This sounds like an interesting plan, but I wouldn't make a warrior just to make money for a&nbsp;&nbsp;monk personally, unless you really want a warrior for its own sake. Most people trying to make money for another char will create druids or wizards and run them to the point that they can port (lvl 29), but this takes a long time. Personally, if you are aiming for cured silk my suggestions are to just pull your monk up by its bootstraps since it's not that expensive at only 1pp/ac.<br><br>I start new monks out as follows:<br><br>1) take agnostic so you can start in Qeynos (every noice this is Sony EQ backwards?) because it is less crowded than Freeport.<br>2) Kill skels with a cracked staff when you see one and wield it primary. Any extra ones you can sell for around a plat. And always kill anything with a weapon.<br>3) Don't sell to guy at gate, he rips you off.<br>4) take up fishing for rusty daggers to sell, and sandles to wear.<br>5) At lvl 3 venture in hills ask for a sow and camo from a druid and run to Halas.<br>6) Start your polar bear quest for leather, the weight won't hurt much at this level<br>7) Group often and ask if anyone tailors, you might be able to make a deal for cured silk or at least raw silk.<br><br>If you are new this will be quicker than starting another char first. If you already have an older monk then try finding a guild and asking for the guild price on cured silk. If you get the silk yourself and buy or brew the kiola you can usually get it for free or very cheap.<br><br>Hope this helps.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
